{
  "description": "EPIC_07 ISSUE_03 (#51) known-correlation-structure fixture for the clustered bootstrap (SPEC S13.5, S21 glossary 'clustered bootstrap'). Three event groups EVT-A/EVT-B/EVT-C, each with 10 perfectly-correlated markets (same probability_ppm, same baseline_executable_price_pips/ask, same resolution outcome within a group), for 30 forecasts total. Every forecast carries `correlation_group_id` equal to its group. Per-market Brier terms (using the shared brier_skill formula 1 - Sum(forecast_term)/Sum(baseline_term), forecast_term=(p-o)^2, baseline_term=(baseline_ppm-o)^2, baseline_ppm = baseline_executable_price_pips*100): EVT-A p=0.8 ask=0.7 outcome=yes -> forecast_term=(0.8-1)^2=0.04, baseline_term=(0.7-1)^2=0.09. EVT-B p=0.3 ask=0.2 outcome=no -> forecast_term=(0.3-0)^2=0.09, baseline_term=(0.2-0)^2=0.04. EVT-C p=0.6 ask=0.5 outcome=yes -> forecast_term=(0.6-1)^2=0.16, baseline_term=(0.5-1)^2=0.25. Overall point estimate (summed over all 30 forecasts, or equivalently one occurrence of each group since every market within a group is identical): forecast_sum = 10*(0.04+0.09+0.16) = 2.9, baseline_sum = 10*(0.09+0.04+0.25) = 3.8; skill = 1 - 2.9/3.8 = 1 - 29/38 = 9/38 = 0.2368421052631... -> floor(9/38 * 1_000_000) = 236_842 ppm. Clustering is by `correlation_group_id`, not by market_ticker: there are only 3 independent clusters (EVT-A, EVT-B, EVT-C) among these 30 markets, so a cluster bootstrap resamples 3 clusters with replacement from {A,B,C} -- effective_n == 3, not 30. Because there are only 3 distinct clusters, a 3-draw-with-replacement bootstrap replicate is always one of the 10 multisets of {A,B,C} (order does not matter for the summed statistic): using the single-market terms above (ratio-invariant to the x10 market-count scaling), the skill for a multiset {x,y,z} is 1 - (f_x+f_y+f_z)/(b_x+b_y+b_z) where f_A=0.04,b_A=0.09; f_B=0.09,b_B=0.04; f_C=0.16,b_C=0.25. The 10 multisets and their exact skill fractions: AAA=1-0.12/0.27=5/9=0.555555... (max; floor 555_555 ppm, ceil 555_556 ppm), AAB=1-0.17/0.22=5/22=0.227272... (floor 227_272, ceil 227_273), AAC=1-0.24/0.43=19/43=0.441860... (floor 441_860, ceil 441_861), ABB=1-0.22/0.17=-5/17=-0.294117... (floor -294_118, ceil -294_117), ABC=1-0.29/0.38=9/38=0.236842... (floor 236_842, ceil 236_843 -- this is also the full-sample point estimate), ACC=1-0.36/0.59=23/59=0.389830... (floor 389_830, ceil 389_831), BBB=1-0.27/0.12=-5/4=-1.25 exact (min; -1_250_000 ppm, floor==ceil), BBC=1-0.34/0.33=-1/33=-0.030303... (floor -30_304, ceil -30_303), BCC=1-0.41/0.54=13/54=0.240740... (floor 240_740, ceil 240_741), CCC=1-0.48/0.75=9/25=0.36 exact (360_000 ppm, floor==ceil). The full floor/ceil-rounded support set therefore spans from BBB's exact -1_250_000 (the minimum) up to AAA's ceil-rounded 555_556 (the maximum); any 1000-replicate seeded bootstrap's order-statistic CI bounds must fall within this 10-value (20-candidate, some coincident) support set. An 'unclustered reference' is computed by stripping every forecast's `correlation_group_id` (making each of the 30 markets its own singleton cluster, effective_n == 30) and calling the same public `brier_skill_ci` API again on the group-id-stripped inputs: with 10x the effective cluster count, the resampling variance collapses and the resulting CI must be materially narrower than the 3-cluster CI above -- this is the concrete demonstration that ignoring correlation structure produces overconfident (too-narrow) intervals.",
